param_dist_combined = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200],  # Number of boosting stages
    'learning_rate': [0.07, 0.08, 0.01],  # Learning rate (step size)
    'max_depth': [3, 4, 5],  # Maximum depth of the trees
    'subsample': [0.5, 0.6, 0.8],  # Fraction of samples used for fitting each base learner
    'min_samples_split': list(range(12, 16)),  # Minimum samples required to split an internal node
    'min_samples_leaf': list(range(14, 19)),  # Minimum samples required to be at a leaf node
    'max_features': [10, 'sqrt', 'log2']  # Number of features to consider when looking for the best split
}

In [21]:
# Data Preprocessing
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaled_sales = scaler.fit_transform(sales_data)

# Generate time series sequences
length = 12
train_size = int(len(scaled_sales) * 0.8)
test_size = len(scaled_sales) - train_size
train, test = scaled_sales[0:train_size], scaled_sales[train_size:len(scaled_sales)]

train_generator = TimeseriesGenerator(train, train, length=length, batch_size=1)
validation_generator = TimeseriesGenerator(test, test, length=length, batch_size=1)

In [18]:
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import GRU, Dense, Dropout, Input

# Define the input shape
input_shape = (length, n_features)

# Build the GRU model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Input(shape=input_shape))  # Add an Input layer to specify the input shape
model.add(GRU(units=128, activation='relu', return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(GRU(units=64, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(1))

model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

print(model.summary())

def calculate_zero_crossings(audio_path):
    data, sr = librosa.load(audio_path)
    zero_crossings = librosa.zero_crossings(data, pad=False)
    zero_crossing_count = sum(zero_crossings)
    return zero_crossing_count

for idx, (audio_path, genre) in enumerate(audio_files):

🎼 Harmonizing with Machine Learning: Model Building

1. Fully Connected Neural Network (Dense Network) 🤖¶

A Fully Connected Neural Network (FCNN), or Dense Network, is a fundamental neural network architecture. This model consists of layers where each neuron in one layer is connected to every neuron in the next layer. This connectivity allows the network to learn complex patterns in the data, making it highly effective for various classification tasks.

  • Key Features:
    • Dense layers with ReLU activation
    • Suitable for capturing complex patterns
    • Effective for various classification tasks

2. 1D Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) with Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) 🌐¶

This hybrid model leverages the feature extraction capabilities of Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and the sequential processing strengths of Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks. The CNN layers capture local temporal patterns in the audio data, while the LSTM layers capture long-term dependencies, making this model particularly powerful for audio classification tasks.

  • Key Features:
    • Combines CNN and LSTM for robust feature extraction
    • Captures both local and sequential patterns
    • Ideal for processing audio data

Why These Models? 🤔¶

Each of these models brings unique strengths to the table:

  • The Dense Network is straightforward and effective for capturing complex patterns.
  • The CNN-LSTM Hybrid excels at processing sequential data with local patterns, ming beautiful with data! 🎶

ng beautiful with data! 🎶

def plotValidate(history):
    """
    Plot training and validation metrics with enhanced visualization.

    Parameters:
    history (tf.keras.callbacks.History): Training history returned from model.fit.
    """
    # Extract metrics from history
    metrics = history.history

    # Print the best validation accuracy
    print("Best Validation Accuracy:", max(metrics.get("val_accuracy", [0])))

    # Plot loss and accuracy
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))

    # Colors for the plots
    color_train_accuracy = '#1f77b4'
    color_val_accuracy = '#ff7f0e'
    color_train_loss = '#2ca02c'
    color_val_loss = '#d62728'

    # Plot accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(metrics['accuracy'], color=color_train_accuracy, linestyle='-', marker='o', label='Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(metrics['val_accuracy'], color=color_val_accuracy, linestyle='--', marker='x', label='Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)

    # Plot loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(metrics['loss'], color=color_train_loss, linestyle='-', marker='o', label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(metrics['val_loss'], color=color_val_loss, linestyle='--', marker='x', label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)

    # Improve layout and show plots
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    BatchNormalization(),
    Dropout(0.3),
    
    Dense(256, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.01)),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dropout(0.3),
    
    Dense(128, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.01)),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dropout(0.3),
    
    Dense(64, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.01)),
    BatchNormalization(),

])

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, LSTM, Dense

# Define the model
model_2 = Sequential()
model_2.add(Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], 1)))  # Add an Input layer to specify the input shape
model_2.add(Conv1D(64, kernel_size=3, activation='relu'))
model_2.add(BatchNormalization())
model_2.add(MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2))
model_2.add(Dropout(0.3))

model_2.add(LSTM(128, return_sequences=True))
model_2.add(BatchNormalization())
model_2.add(Dropout(0.3))

model_2.add(LSTM(64, return_sequences=False))
model_2.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dropout(0.3))

model_2.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_2.add(BatchNormalization())
model_2.add(Dropout(0.3))

model_2.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model_2.add(BatchNormalization())
model_2.add(Dropout(0.3))

model_2.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

# Compile the model with a learning rate schedule
lr_schedule = CosineDecay(initial_learning_rate=0.001, decay_steps=1000, alpha=0.1)
optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule)

model_2.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])

# Print the model summary
print(model_2.summary())

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

# Initialize the decision tree model with specific parameters
tree_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(
    criterion='entropy',                # Function to measure the quality of a split
    splitter='best',                 # Strategy to choose the split at each node
    max_depth=100,                    # Maximum depth of the tree
    min_samples_split=3,             # Minimum number of samples required to split an internal node
    min_samples_leaf=5,              # Minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node
    max_features=150,             # Number of features to consider when looking for the best split
    max_leaf_nodes=700,               # Maximum number of leaf nodes
    min_impurity_decrease=0.001,      # Minimum impurity decrease required to split a node
    class_weight='balanced',         # Weights associated with classes
    random_state=0                  # Seed for the random number generator
)

# Accuracy values for the models
accuracy_log_reg = 0.738991
accuracy_svm = 0.905524
accuracy_tree = 0.671737
accuracy_fc_nn = 0.9151  # Fully Connected Neural Network
accuracy_lstm_cnn = 0.7762  # LSTM-CNN Model

# Create a summary table
summary_data = {
    "Model": ["Logistic Regression", "SVM", "Decision Tree", "Fully Connected Neural Network", "LSTM-CNN"],
    "Accuracy": [accuracy_log_reg, accuracy_svm, accuracy_tree, accuracy_fc_nn, accuracy_lstm_cnn]
}

# Convert to DataFrame
summary_df = pd.DataFrame(summary_data)

# Determine the winner
winner = summary_df.loc[summary_df['Accuracy'].idxmax(), 'Model']

# Add a 'Winner' column to the DataFrame
summary_df['Winner'] = summary_df['Model'].apply(lambda x: 'Yes' if x == winner else 'No')

# Print the summary table
print("Model Performance Summary:")
summary_df
